 To calculate the probability, we need to consider all possible cases for the gender distribution of the committee. 

For exactly one boy and one girl:
{eq}{10 \choose 1} \times {15 \choose 1} \times {23 \choose 3}{/eq}

For exactly two boys and one girl:
{eq}{10 \choose 2} \times {15 \choose 1} \times {23 \choose 2}{/eq}

For exactly three boys and one girl:
{eq}{10 \choose 3} \times {15 \choose 1} \times {23 \choose 1}{/eq}

For exactly four boys and one girl:
{eq}{10 \choose 4} \times {15 \choose 1}{/eq}

Now, calculate the probabilities for each case and sum them up:

{eq}\begin{align*}
P(\text{at least 1 boy and 1 girl}) &= \frac{{10 \choose 1} \times {15 \choose 1} \times {23 \choose 3} + {10 \choose 2} \times {15 \choose 1} \times {23 \choose 2} + {10 \choose 3} \times {15 \choose 1} \times {23 \choose 1} + {10 \choose 4} \times {15 \choose 1}}{\binom{25}{5}}
\end{align*}{/eq}

Simplifying the expression, we get:

{eq}\begin{align*}
P(\text{at least 1 boy and 1 girl}) &= \frac{23295}{5313}{/eq}

The final probability is approximately 0.438, which can also be expressed as a percentage.

solution:
Let $z = x + yi,$ where $x$ and $y$ are real numbers.  Then $|x + yi - 5 - i| = |(x - 5) + (y - 1)i| = 5,$ so
\[(x - 5)^2 + (y - 1)^2 = 25.\]This simplifies to $x^2 - 10x + y^2 - 2y = -1.$

Also,
\begin{align*}
|z - 1 + 2i|^2 + |z - 9 - 4i|^2 &= |x + yi - 1 + 2i|^2 + |x + yi - 9 - 4i|^2 \\
&= |(x - 1) + (y + 2)i|^2 + |(x - 9) + (y - 4)i|^2 \\
&= (x - 1)^2 + (y + 2)^2 + (x - 9)^2 + (y - 4)^2 \\
&= 2x^2 - 20x + 2y^2 - 4y + 102 \\
&= 2(x^2 - 10x + y^2 - 2y) + 102 \\
&= 2(-1) + 102 = 100.
\end{align*}Thus, the expression is always equal to $\boxed{100}.$

Geometrically, the condition $|z - 5 - i| = 5$ states that $z$ lies on a circle centered at $5 + i$ with radius 5.

